<TEXT>
the government began a new effort 
monday to rally nato allies behind its proposal for superpower 
talks on reducing shortrange nuclear weapons which has caused a 
dispute with the united states and britain 
foreign minister hansdietrich genscher was quoted as saying 
west germanys argument must have special weight because it is 
the alliances front line and a war with such battlefieldrange 
weapons would be fought on its territory 
both the united states and britain say the negotiations proposed 
by chancellor helmut kohl might endanger western security 
the new york times reported tuesday that the elements of a 
compromise have begun to emerge with a us proposal submitted to 
nato headquarters in brussels belgium 
quoting unidentified diplomats from several nations the 
newspaper said washington proposed wednesday that the alliance 
decide to upgrade the weapons and then announce unilateral 
reductions nato would then challenge the soviets to make cuts to 
the lower levels 
in washington white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said 
monday that the united states remains committed to a mixture of 
nato conventional and nuclear forces called flexible response as 
a deterrent to attack 
the west german position demonstrates the special strength 
that nato has fitzwater said our allies can debate quite 
vigorously these issues yet maintain the basic strength of our 
unity 
our position remains that keeping the peace requires a strong 
nato alliance and a policy of flexible response 
genschers remarks were the first official west german comment 
since a meeting sunday in which prime minister margaret thatcher of 
britain tried but failed to change kohls mind on the issue 
in pursuit of support for the west german position kohl plans 
to visit rome on tuesday and genscher will go to paris 
italy has said it agrees with west germany that negotiations on 
the shortrange weapons should begin but france has not made its 
position clear west germany claims the support of seven of the 16 
north atlantic treaty orgnization members 
in an interview with the frankfurter rundschau genscher was 
quoted as saying this is not a new demand that has only now been 
made by us and other alliance partners this concerns putting into 
effect an intention which has already been stated in two alliance 
decisions 
his ministry made copies of the interview available to other 
news organizations before publication in the papers tuesday 
editions 
genscher has noted previously the nato decision at summits in 
1987 and 1988 that negotiations on shortrange nuclear weapons 
should be held at some point the united states and britain say 
this is not the time 
naturally the german view must have a special weight because 
the lance rockets are on our soil and because our army represents 
the largest conventional contribution in west germany to the 
common western security genscher said 
west germanys army has about 500000 soldiers most of the 
alliances shortrange lance rockets are on its territory and would 
be used there in a war 
kohl and genscher say nato should not pass up opportunities to 
negotiate in important areas of disarmament and they insist the 
time is right for taking up the battlefieldrange weapons the 
chancellor has said he wants the talks to begin soon but has 
not proposed a timetable 
a west german government official said privately monday the 
chancellor was optimistic about a compromise 
us and british officials say starting negotiations now could 
lead to elimination of the shortrange weapons and increase the 
threat from the soviet blocs superior conventional forces 
after the meeting with mrs thatcher on sunday kohl said he 
does not favor pulling the lance missiles out of west germany 
under the present circumstances 
gen john galvin the american who commands nato forces in 
europe was quoted as saying he did not believe there was 
disagreement on strategy within the alliance 
in an interview for publication tuesday the newspaper die welt 
quoted galvin as saying recent statements make it very clear 
that there are no differences in the grand strategy the importance 
of nuclear deterrence is recognized 
</TEXT>
