<TEXT>
when the prime ministers political secretary 
committed suicide many saw him as a victim of the money politics 
entwined with japanese culture and tradition 
beside such westernstyle institutions as a parliament and free 
elections japan has customs that demand exchanges of gifts and 
favors and lingering ideals of absolute loyalty 
japanese politicians spend campaign money in a very personal 
manner 
voters expect their representatives not only to bring 
porkbarrel projects to the district but to help their children 
find jobs in tokyo attend weddings and send donations to funerals 
political secretaries spend much of their time going to family 
ceremonies and delivering obligatory gifts 
results of a survey published in the newspaper asahi said a 
legislator or his representative attends on average 265 funerals 
a month 
ihei aoki for three decades prime minister noboru takeshitas 
closest aide may have killed himself wednesday because more than 
1 million in donations and loans he received from the recruit co 
helped bring down his boss who had announced the day before he 
would resign 
the tragic case of aokis suicide pathetically calls for a 
drastic reform of the moneyoriented structure of politics the 
daily yomiuri said in an editorial 
asahi said political aides function as cloaks that cover up 
foul play of 13 politicians linked to the recruit scandal it 
noted six took donations in aides names rather than their own 
political secretaries who would be called legislative 
assistants in the united states carry a burden imposed by the 
moneydriven election system most spend hardly any time drafting 
legislation a job generally handled by bureaucrats 
aokis main task as secretary to a top leader was to raise 
money from big business and distribute it to legislators said 
kotaru nogami chief political editor of the kyodo news service 
secretaries of legislators in turn pass some of the largesse 
on to their districts 
basically a secretary does everything and anything he is told 
to do and he has to carry out any order to perfection even though 
specific guidelines are not given said chris redl of phoenix 
ariz a political secretary to a legislator of the governing 
liberal democratic party 
when he began working in japan redl said he was surprised to 
see aides in funny costumes dancing to entertain constituents at a 
local festival 
he said he was exhausted by the dawnto2am schedule of 
courtesy calls and parties with supporters in the hokkaido district 
of his legislator shizuo sato 
i talked to another secretary who had to do this all the 
time the american said he told me its like the old days 
you have to be ready to die for your shogun 
when aoki killed himself many people were reminded of the 
suicide in 1976 of former prime minister kakuei tanakas driver 
who had carried payoff money in the lockheed scandal tanaka 
eventually was convicted on a bribery charge 
after the lockheed scandal there was a lot of discussion of 
political reform but it was never carried out nogami said 
a partial reform limited donations but the recruit case 
revealed ways around it buying many tickets to fundraising 
parties and selling shares at bargain prices before offering them 
for public sale 
recruit was limited to contributing 115000 a year to all 
politicians in three years however takeshita alone got more than 
15 million from the company in donations stocksale profits 
loans and proceeds from ticket purchases all of it went through 
aokis hands 
such huge sums of money are needed in part because taxes cover 
only a fraction of what it costs to run the parliament 
the recruit scandal was born of the system said sato 47 
the young americans boss he is a member of the governing partys 
cmmittee on reform and wants more government funds so legislators 
will be less dependent on contributions 
in the tiny office the government provides he told an 
interviewer the budget from the government allows for only two 
aides i have 15 
his monthly travel allowance of 500 covers just a quarter of 
what he spends visiting his constituency 
sato depends on a patron former prime minister yasuhiro 
nakasone for political funds and in return backs nakasone in 
intraparty maneuvers 
patrons like nakasone or takeshita lead liberal democratic 
factions that operate almost as separate parties particularly in 
raising money 
explaining how japanese politicians spend campaign funds in 
their districts sato said its different from america a simple 
television ad wont get votes its a matter of obligation and 
human feelings 
americans might see the exchanges of favors and money as graft 
or votebuying but in japan they generally are considered social 
custom 
contributions by recruit were at the top level of an 
interlocking system of gifts and obligations stretching down to 
ordinary citizens 
some japanese say they dont mind politicians collecting large 
amounts of money because they usually recirculate it rather than 
enriching themselves 
giving gift envelopes of cash at weddings funerals and bon 
voyage parties even between parents and children at the new year 
is a matter of etiquette in japan 
a parliamentary survey indicated young legislators spent an 
average of 274000 a year on cash gifts for funerals weddings 
community festivals and local clubs 
when a politician gives money at a funeral its not because 
hes a politician but because its a matter of japanese custom 
sato said now it may be necessary for us to distance ourselves 
from japanese habits 
among reforms an advisory group suggested to takeshita last week 
was prohibiting parliament members from giving money at weddings 
and funerals 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

