<DOCNO> AP890501-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the riots that shook the kingdom have 
turned jordans focus toward internal problems and made the country 
less of a factor in the israelpalestinian controversy over the 
future of the occupied territories 
it has become increasingly clear that king hussein was serious 
last year when he vowed never to negotiate on behalf of the 
palestinians saying it is a matter between israel and the 
palestinians themselves 
the king was bowing to the obvious the palestinian uprising on 
the israelioccupied west bank of the jordan river which he ruled 
until 1967 showed he had little remaining loyalty there it had 
shifted to the palestine liberation organization 
even the idea of a confederation between jordan and a 
palestinian state a proposal to make palestinian independence 
palatable to israel seems only remotely possible these days 
hussein for months has said he will consider a confederation 
only after a palestinian state is created and only if palestinians 
there and jordanians in his country vote for it 
many oldline jordanians or east bankers oppose a 
confederation because it could give palestinians a larger say in 
jordanian affairs palestinians already make up half of jordans 3 
million people 
palestinians were almost nowhere to be seen in the four days of 
rioting that began on april 18 and rocked more than a dozen towns 
and villages in southern jordan the bedrock of support for hussein 
the rioting in which at least nine people were killed was 
sparked by governmentimposed price increases but contained a cry 
by east bankers that hussein pay attention to their problems and 
give them a greater voice in running the country 
some have resented the prosperity and political prominence of 
palestinians who were granted full citizenship when jordan merged 
with the west bank in 1950 some also hold a grudge from 1969 and 
1970 when plo guerrillas began to set up a state within a state in 
jordan often harassing east bankers at guerrilla roadblocks 
husseins selection thursday of field marshal zeid bin shaker 
the former army commander as prime minister partly answered that 
plea 
bin shaker a man of bedouin stock commands wide loyalty in the 
armed forces which are still a favored occupation for bedouin 
youth he also was prominent in crushing the guerrilla movement in 
1970 
he replaces zaid rifai whose jordanian birth was not enough in 
the eyes of many east bank eyes to compensate for his fathers 
palestinian origins 
hussein will not renounce the palestinians in jordan itself he 
has woven them into the fabric of his society along with smaller 
immigrant groups such as armenians and circassians 
but the king has demanded they act as jordanians and his 
security forces watch closely for any expressions of domestic 
palestinian nationalism 
israeli leaders still speak often of turning part of the west 
bank back to jordan or putting it under the control of jordanian 
security forces 
but hardline israelis refuse to give up any of the west bank or 
consider any form of palestinian entity they say there already is 
a palestine jordan 
however some of the resentments that led to the recent rioting 
demonstrate that jordan is not a palestinian state 
no amount of introspection will keep jordan from being an 
essential player in middle east peace maneuvering it shares 
israels longest border and is permanently threatened by a conflict 
that has twice swamped jordan with refugees 
the king has vowed to maintain his support of the palestinians 
in the occupied lands and has been an important moderating force on 
the plos negotiating demands his abandonment of claims to the 
west bank helped push the plo to focus its attention on ending 
israeli occupation there 
and the palestinian organization followed husseins longstanding 
appeal that it formally endorse israels right to exist 
that led the united states to open a dialogue with the plo in 
december and turn its gaze away from jordan as the answer to the 
41year conflict 
hussein is urging israelis to do the same 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
editors note john rice correspondent for the associated press 
in amman jordan has covered the arabisraeli conflict since 1984 
 
</TEXT>
