<TEXT>
the use of socalled tropical oils by us 
food manufacturers has fallen considerably in recent years but the 
agriculture department says it wont make much difference 
economically 
imported products such as palm oil palm kernel oil and coconut 
oil have been attacked vigorously by many us farm and consumer 
interests because of their high levels of saturated fats and 
possible effects on health 
the departments economic research service says the united 
states used about 145 billion pounds of fats and oils in food 
products in the last year but that only 550 million pounds or 4 
percent were tropical oils 
soybean oil accounted for more than 10 billion pounds corn oil 
950 million pounds and cottonseed oil 800 million animal fats 
lard and tallow totaled about 11 billion pounds other sources 
of vegetable oil include sunflower seed and rapeseed 
major edible uses of fats and oils are salad and cooking oils 
baking and frying fats and margarine 
economists bob cummings and jim schaub said that use of tropical 
oils in the united states may average about 184 billion pounds 
since 1985 but the portion used in food products is expected to 
average only about 650 million pounds a year down from the record 
16 billion pounds in the mid1970s 
in 1986 the american soybean association after watching palm 
oil and other tropical oils nudge into the lucrative us market 
launched a campaign highlighting the health benefits of soybean 
oils relatively low saturated fat content 
cummings and schaub writing in the may issue of agricultural 
outlook magazine said the soybean people were joined by the 
national heart savers association which began promoting the use of 
oils low in saturated fats 
tropical oil interests deny adverse health effects and the 
malaysian palm oil growers council has mounted an information 
campaign and has underwritten medical studies to support its case 
but cummings and schaub said saturated fats have been linked 
with high blood cholesterol levels and heart disease citing last 
years report by the us surgeon general recommending reduced 
intake of dietary fats especially saturated fats 
several major food companies have eliminated tropical oils in 
all or most of their products and others plan to follow 
if edible use of tropical oils were cut 50 percent the effect 
on us fats and oils markets would be marginal because these oils 
are only a small portion of total use the economists said in 
their report substitute oils would capture some of the small 
market share held by tropical oils 
the report added prices also would be little affected those 
manufacturers using large quantities of relatively lowpriced palm 
oil would experience the largest impact consumers would hardly be 
affected because tropical oils account for only a small part of 
the price of finished food products 
cummings and schaub also said that a 50 percent reduction in 
us food use of tropical oils would have little effect on us 
imports and world trade and the effect on suppliers such as 
malaysia would likewise be minor 
</TEXT>
