a final order is expected to be issued soon by 
the agriculture department clearing the way for a watermelon 
checkoff plan to finance a national research and promotion program 
the departments agricultural marketing service said the next 
steps after the formal order is to hold meetings and solicit 
nominations for a 29member board that will oversee the program 
those nominations are expected to be submitted by the end of july 
after a board is selected a proposed spending budget will be 
drawn up and submitted for review the agency says it may be fall 
or later before everything is wrapped up 
in any case the watermelon assessments which are mandatory 
but can be refunded are expected to be ready for 1990 production 
the assessments and the program were authorized by congress in 
the 1985 farm law a referendum was held in february in which 
approximately 52 percent of the growers and 56 percent of the 
handlers approved the plan 
agency officials said an estimated 7000 watermelon producers 
and handlers would be covered by the checkoff program 
the assessment to be recommended by the board and then set by 
usda can be levied at rate of up to two cents per 100 pounds of 
watermelons sold by producers and two cents per 100 pounds for 
handlers 
all producers of watermelons having five acres or more and first 
handlers are required to pay the assessment a grower of five acres 
or more who also handles watermelons would have to pay both 
assessments 
