as a teenager in poland during world war ii 
irene opdyke risked death at the hands of the gestapo by hiding 12 
jewish friends in the basement and attic of a german officers 
villa where she worked 
all survived the holocaust as did countless others who were 
saved because mrs opdyke shared information overheard from gestapo 
officers planning roundups in jewish communities 
last week an old war debt was repaid 
administrators at the jewish home for the aged in the san 
fernando valley community of reseda waived admissions policies and 
admitted ms opdykes 80yearold husband william to their 
alzheimers disease unit 
we violated all the rules hes not from our region we are 
sectarian we are so short of beds but there are certain times 
when there are no rules this is one of those times executive 
director sheldon blumenthal said in caring for bill we are 
repaying a debt to her we owe her 
opdyke is one of only a few nonjews at the 875bed facility 
that provides communal living for old people 
mrs opdyke 68 said she vowed to help her jewish friends when 
she saw the way hitlers army treated jews during the 1939 invasion 
of poland she called it a nightmare that changed my life 
i saw a man with a white beard and a little white hat running 
carrying a torah she said little ones were screaming mama 
mama i saw a soldier pull a baby out of its mothers arms and 
