<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to hear a bush 
administration appeal aimed at allowing the government to collect 
potentially hundreds of millions of dollars in taxes from 
multinational corporations 
in a case involving goodyear tire and rubber co the court said 
it will review a ruling that allows multinationals to use foreign 
tax laws to reduce their us taxes 
the case stems from operations of goodyears british subsidiary 
in the early 1970s 
the ohiobased corporations subsidiary incurred net losses in 
1972 and 1973 at least under british tax law the subsidiarys 
1973 loss included british tax deductions that were not allowed 
under american tax law 
as a result the british government refunded to the subsidiary 
the tax payments it made there for 1970 and 1971 
the refunds prompted the us internal revenue service to 
recompute the taxes it said goodyear owed in this country 
multinationals are entitled to claim a share of taxes paid by 
subsidiaries overseas as credits against us taxes 
in the goodyear case since american law did not recognize the 
1973 deductions permitted the company in great britain the 
corporations loss was converted into a profit 
the redetermination had the further effect of wiping out for 
us tax purposes the foreign tax credits previously allowed in 
1970 and 1971 
as a result the irs assessed goodyear 791240 in taxes and 
interest for 1970 and 1971 
goodyear then sued in the us claims court saying the irs 
erred in applying american law instead of british law to determine 
the companys accumulated profits 
the claims court ruled against goodyear but a federal appeals 
court here reversed the decision last august 
the appeals court said a multinational company is entitled to 
use a foreign nations tax laws to determine accumulated profits 
made by a subsidiary in that country 
administration officials said the ruling could have enormous 
importance for us tax revenues 
justice department lawyers in the appeal acted on today said 
more than 25000 foreign subsidiaries of us companies are doing 
business in more than 100 countries the government said its most 
recent figures show the companies claimed more than 9 billion in 
foreign tax credits in 1982 
the irs is reviewing 150 million in claimed refunds in such 
cases and expects the appeals court ruling will prompt an 
additional 750 million in refund claims 
the government appeal conceded that the impact of the appeals 
court ruling has been blunted by a 1986 change in us tax law that 
may mean multinationals no longer will be able to use a foreign 
countrys calculation of its accumulated profits for most future 
tax payments here 
the case is us vs goodyear 881474 
</TEXT>
