<TEXT>
the supreme court today allowed the government 
to impose annual licensing fees of around 1 million for nuclear 
power plants 
the justices without comment rejected an appeal by 29 
companies that own or operate nuclear reactors 
the licensing fee for nuclear plants was adopted by the nuclear 
regulatory commission under a 1986 budget bill passed by congress 
the measure the consolidated omnibus budget reconciliation act 
authorizes the nrc to pay for onethird of its annual budget by 
assessing such fees 
the commission imposed a fee of 950000 last year on each 
holder of a nuclear plant license the fee is expected to be more 
than 1 million for the current fiscal year 
the us circuit court of appeals here upheld the fee last may 
the appeals court rejected arguments that the fee should be tied 
directly to services the nrc performs for the benefit of a 
particular nuclear plant 
the appeals court also said the fee is a constitutional 
delegation of congress power to impose taxes 
the appeals court said congress may delegate the tax power 
where adequate standards are set for implementation of 
congressional intent 
the fee bears a reasonable relationship to regulatory services 
performed by the nrc the appeals court added 
the justices last week unanimously upheld federal safety user 
fees imposed on pipelines that transport natural gas and 
hazardous liquids 
the case acted on today is florida power amp light vs us 
88234 
