<TEXT>
a federal judge today refused to stop the 
federal government from requiring atlantic and gulf coast shrimpers 
to equip their nets with a device intended to preserve sea turtles 
in danger of extinction 
louisiana attorney general william guste had filed suit on 
behalf of gulf coast shrimpers who say the turtle excluder 
devices commonly called teds are dangerous to pull unnecessary 
and reduce their catch 
environmentalists maintain the devices will help save the 
endangered kemps ridley sea turtle from extinction by reducing the 
number of turtles caught by the shrimpers 
us district judge patrick carr issued his ruling today after 
holding a rare telephone hearing friday on gustes request for a 
temporary restraining order to block the requirement 
congress has the power and authority to suspend the 
enforcement of the use of teds until further studies are made but 
chose not to do so carr wrote in his brief ruling the courts 
have no such power or authority 
if this law isnt changed it will mean that the entire 
shrimping industry is out of business tee john mialjevich 
president of concerned shrimpers said saturday 
its not that we dont want to save turtles its that we want 
to feed our families 
mialjevich said his group represents 2000 shrimpers from north 
carolina to brownsville texas 
teds fit into the mouth of trawls a type of net and have trap 
doors that let turtles escape shrimpers argue that they are too 
easily clogged with debris and that a significant portion of their 
catch escapes with the turtles 
shrimpers won a 60day reprieve from hefty fines that were to 
have gone into effect today for boats not equipped with teds 
commerce secretary robert mosbacher last week told the coast 
guard to issue only warnings through june 30 instead of fines of 
up to 10000 to violators along the gulf and atlantic coasts 
shrimpers disclaim responsibility for most of the 11000 turtle 
deaths estimated by the national oceanographic and atmospheric 
administration each year 
ted shepard director of the 400member louisiana shrimpers 
association which is also fighting the teds said that kemps sea 
turtles are uncommon in the areas that his louisiana members fish 
adding theyre in the atlantic and off the coast of florida 
shrimpers have proposed alternatives mialjevich said including 
a 25 fee on shrimping licences each year dedicated to hatching and 
growing the turtles 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

