<TEXT>
the supreme court today revived an indiana 
prison inmates lawsuit ruling unanimously that the suit should 
not have been automatically ruled frivolous 
the justices said a federal trial judge was wrong in finding 
harry williams srs suit frivolous because it failed to state a 
claim on which a court could grant williams some relief 
such a failure to comply with the federal rules of civil 
procedure does not automatically make a lawsuit frivolous justice 
thurgood marshall wrote for the court 
williams an inmate at the indiana state reformatory sued 
various prison officials in 1986 
his complaint said he had been diagnosed by a doctor at the 
indiana state prison as having a small brain tumor that affected 
his equilibrium and he should be excused from all work details 
williams suit said that when he was transferred to the 
reformatory doctors refused to treat the tumor and officials 
assigned him to do garmentmanufacturing work 
when he refused to continue working the reformatory 
disciplinary board responded by transferring him to a less 
desirable cellhouse 
the suit however did not allege deliberate indifference on 
the part of prison doctors or officials a necessary allegation in 
such cases when prison inmates allege cruel and unusual punishment 
the case is neitzke vs williams 871882 
</TEXT>
