<TEXT>
former arms negotiator paul warnke criticized 
the bush administration on monday for failing to assert leadership 
and avert an argument raging in the nato alliance over shortrange 
nuclear weapons 
there has been no american leadership whatsoever said 
warnke and as a result we have a very sharp dispute over a 
silly issue 
warnke chief arms negotiator for thenpresident carter 
recommended that the north atlantic treaty organization stick to 
agreements reached in the alliance in 1987 and 1988 to modernize 
us lance tactical missiles in west germany 
at the same time warnke said nato should open negotiations 
with the soviet union about eliminating the entire class of nuclear 
missiles with ranges of under 300 miles and therefore not subject 
to the intermediaterange nuclear force pact which took effect 
last year 
the dispute over modernizing shortrange nuclear weapons has 
pitted west german chancellor helmut kohl against british prime 
minister margaret thatcher and president bush 
kohl and thatcher held what they called frank and intensive 
talks on the issue sunday in deidesheim west germany but parted 
in disagreement 
we still have quite a lot of work to do kohl said after the 
meeting although predicting that an agreement was possible before 
a nato summit in brussels belgium this month 
kohl whose party faces tough elections next year wants nato to 
begin negotiations with the soviet bloc on the issue and to delay 
until at least 1992 a decision on lance modernization 
thatcher said eliminating shortrange nuclear weapons would mean 
that the soviet union will have achieved its objective of getting 
landbased nuclear weapons out of europe this i believe would be 
disastrous 
warnke said nato could finesse the issue by entering 
negotiations while stipulating that the western alliance would not 
eliminate its shortrange nuclear weapons until the sovietled 
warsaw pact sharply reduced its conventional forces in europe 
thereby removing the threat that the lance is intended to deal 
with said warnke 
the existing shortrange force should not be a priority 
warnke said at a breakfast meeting with reporters it does not 
seem to me that we need either to eliminate or modernize tactical 
nuclear systems 
they can only be used if the russians invade western euroupe 
you are not going to blow up the mens room in the kremlin 
with the lance which cannot reach beyond german borders said 
warnke who was assistant secretary of defense from 1967 through 
1969 and the head of the arms control and disarmament agency in 
1977 and 1978 
warnke also urged the bush adminstration to move more quickly to 
take advantage of conventional arms concesssions made by soviet 
