pope john paul ii flew to this french 
indian ocean island monday after urging his flock in the 
impoverished african nation of madagascar to reject contraceptive 
imperialism and abortion 
the pope arrived on this volcanic island about 450 miles east 
of madagascar on the second stop of a nineday tour that will also 
take him to the african nations of zambia and malawi 
he was greeted at the airport by french prime minister michel 
rocard and a french military band playing the marseillaise 
john paul then rode in his glassenclosed popemobile to the 
municipal building to meet privately with rocard and address 
political and church officials he later spoke to local clergy at 
the 19th century cathedral and had dinner with bishops from 
reunion mauritius and the seyechelles 
earlier monday john paul concluded a threeday visit to 
madagascar with an openair mass for about 100000 people in 
fianarantsoa a wineproducing town in the south of the island 
he devoted much of his homily to birth control a pressing issue 
in madagascar where the average citizen earns 250 a year and the 
population of 11 million is growing at an annual rate of 3 percent 
only one in 100 married women in madagascar uses contraception 
according to the world watch institute and western aid agencies 
have sought to promote the use of artificial birth control 
the power to transmit life must be respected said the 
whiterobed pontiff speaking in french from a wooden altar 
overlooking a dirt field near the airport 
you cannot let yourselves be won over by the increasing 
tendency to consider it childbearing secondary or even to want 
to prevent human fertility from expressing itself 
the pope said that if it is necessary for couples to choose 
family planning they must follow methods that respect nature 
he was referring to the only method approved by the roman 
catholic church natural family planning based on abstinence during 
a womans fertile period 
the teaching of the church seems difficult but many couples 
testify that it is possible to follow it and that it is even a 
liberation compared to what we call contraceptive imperialism 
john paul also decried abortion saying families must respect 
the life of the child from conception 
do not accept that abortion is commonplace take care of the 
fragile but human life of the unborn child the dignity of man 
is at stake 
before the ceremony the pope blessed lepers kneeling in the 
sand at the foot of the altar patting each of them on the head 
they came from a nearby leper clinic founded in 1912 by a polish 
jesuit missionary jan beyzym 
i would like to say to those suffering from leprosy and other 
illnesses how much the church wants to bring them consolation 
and comfort how much she loves them 
addressing officials in st denis john paul told islanders they 
should rethink certain ways of life he didnt elaborate but 
local church officials have expressed concern about consumerisim 
and materialism as well as superstition exorcism and satanic cults 
reunion covering 970 square miles has been a french overseas 
department since 1946 it is the richest of the countries on the 
popes trip as a tourist attraction and sugar exporter and also has 
the highest percentage of catholics 90 percent of the 500000 
population 
seventy percent of its people are descendants of the african 
slaves brought to the island by the french in the 1600s 
