forty american and soviet poets and short 
story writers celebrated glasnost on monday by announcing the 
publication of a 345page anthology of some of their best works 
which author bel kaufman called an exchange of our common 
humanity 
the englishlanguage edition of the book titled the human 
experience is published domestically by alfred a knopf for 
1995 the russianlanguage version will be sold to soviet readers 
for two rubles each or about 330 
published under the auspices of the quaker usussr 
committee a philadelphiabased organization that promotes contacts 
between the two countries the anthology is the first joint 
sovietamerican venture in publishing fiction 
contributing american writers and poets include john updike 
joyce carol oates garrison keillor alice walker john sayles and 
stanley kunitz their soviet counterparts include evgeny 
yevtushenko tatiana tolstaya alexander kushner and vasily belov 
the book has to do with our common feelings love hate 
envy worry about our children life and death ms kaufman told 
a news conference at the national press club thats what will 
bring us together more than politics or polemics 
soviet publisher george andjaparidze said the anthology will 
allow the people of both countries to get to know each other and 
understand each other in sharing such mundane concerns as 
getting up with the alarm clock every morning finding a job 
falling in love 
there is nothing in this book about politics or ideology he 
said 
jay worrall jr clerk of the quaker committee said the book 
owes much to mikhail s gorbachevs glasnost policy of opening up 
soviet society and culture 
we owe it all to gorbachev and the quakers said 
andjaparidze who is editor of the khudozhestvennaya literatura 
publishing house in moscow 
some of the writers represented in the book 20 from each 
country will begin three days of informal consultations tuesday at 
the quaker meeting house in washington 
among their other scheduled activities are receptions at the 
folger shakespeare library and the soviet embassy and a poetry 
reading at the library of congress 
prominent soviet literary figure tatiana kudryaviseva said the 
easiest american writers to translate into russian are john 
cheever whose prose is crystal clear and william styron 
whose literary style reminds her of the great russian novelist leo 
tolstoy 
she said it is more difficult to translate the works of donald 
barthelme and joyce carol oates because of their unusual literary 
images and use of american slang 
