<TEXT>
a food and drug administration advisory 
committee on monday recommended approval of an aerosolized version 
of a drug that helps prevent a lifethreatening pneumonia in aids 
patients 
the fda is expected to follow the recommendation and approve an 
aerosol version of pentamidine within weeks said an fda source who 
spoke on the condition of anonymity 
aerosolized pentamidine has been widely available to aids 
patients since the fda in february allowed its distribution to be 
expanded as an experimental medication under government review 
however many insurance plans do not cover experimental drugs 
fda approval would allow nearly universal reimbursement for aids 
patients using the drug 
the advisory committee recommended approval of aerosolized 
pentamidine for preventing initial and recurring bouts of 
pneumocystis carinii pneumonia which causes an estimated 60 
percent of aids deaths 
pentamidine was approved five years ago for use as an injectable 
drug to treat those already suffering from pneumocycstis the spray 
version would make it easier to take into the lungs where the 
pneumonia infection first shows up 
the fda estimated that 50000 patients with aids could benefit 
from the treatment 
the recommendation was based largely on data collected from a 
recent clinical trial conducted by the san francisco community 
consortium a group of physicians who treat aids patients 
the trial which compared the safety of different doses of 
aerosolized pentamidine found that the drug did not provide 
complete protection but did significantly reduce the incidence of 
this pneumonia the fda said 
lyphomed inc of rosemont ill the leading supplier of 
injectable pentamidine is asking to be licensed to supply the 
aerosol version 
