<TEXT>
a paper lunch tray might cost 5 cents more 
than a plastic model that harms the environment but students who 
rid their schools of plastic trays said monday it was worth a 
nickel to help save the earth 
several west milford nj students told of their successful 
antiplastics battle at un headquarters they appeared before 
hundreds of students at a daylong forum sponsored by the un 
environment program 
our battle cry was put your money where your mouth is 
said 15yearold tanja vogt who launched the campaign 
a majority of the students at west milford high school and 
macopin middle school agreed with her and paid an extra nickel for 
their cafeteria lunches to be served on cardboard trays 
the campaign against polystyrene products began when the 
teenager inspired by thomas paines revolutionary pamphlet 
common sense wrote a civics paper calling for their ban 
environmentalists say the products unlike paper take many years 
to break down 
in october i read an article in our local paper that stated 
despite threats to all life the school board continues to use 
polystyrene trays in the school cafeteria she said 
the reason given was pure economics paper trays cost 5 cents 
more than polystyrene 
i was disgusted i knew the environment was worth an extra 
nickel and i was very confident that my peers would agree she 
said 
for one week last autumn the schools gave the students a 
choice pay 120 for lunch on plastic or 125 for a meal on a 
paper tray 
seventytwo percent of the high school students and 86 percent 
of the middle school students paid the extra nickel for paper trays 
the board of education voted in december to stop purchasing 
polystyrene for the townships schools effective feb 1 
the students have launched a letterwriting campaign to persuade 
every school in new jersey to abolish the use of foam plastics 
kurtiz schneid 16 said the success of the antiplastics 
campaign led to formation of a west milford ecology club and to new 
initiatives 
i personally visited our local mcdonalds dressed as ronald 
mctoxic to emphasize our opposition to foam packaging he said 
