<TEXT>
state inspectors resumed investigations of 
accidents and safety complaints at businesses on monday nearly two 
years after gov george deukmejian virtually dismantled their 
agency 
all 21 district offices around the state opened for business 
today said richard stephens said spokesman for the state 
industrial relations department that oversees the california 
occupational safety and health administration or calosha 
the agency is being restored under terms of a statewide ballot 
measure last november that reversed the republican governors 
decision 
in july 1987 deukmejian cut most of the funding for the 7 
million staterun program as a costsaving measure his action 
turned over to the federal government the responsibility for 
monitoring job safety in the private sector where 105 million 
californians work 
all that remained of calosha was an inspection program for 
californias 17 million state and local government workers 
but a coalition of labor environmental business medical and 
education groups spearheaded proposition 97 to restore calosha 
saying the federal occupational safety and health administration 
provided workers with far fewer protections than the state agency 
voters passed the initiative by a margin of 54 percent to 46 
percent 
under a federalstate agreement announced last month inspectors 
for both agencies will police worker safety in california for the 
next five months as the state department of industrial relations 
brings calosha back to life 
as the state program returns to full strength the federal 
presence will be phased out so the state can assume full control on 
oct 1 
theyll have some growing pains but we anticipate calosha 
will be back on stream very rapidly said richard munn of the 
associated general contractors of california which pushed for 
restoring calosha 
about 140 state inspectors were on the job monday with the 
number scheduled to climb gradually to 214 stephens said state 
inspectors will respond to all complaints of unsafe working 
conditions in the private sector 
during the transition the federal osha will continue to conduct 
regularly scheduled inspections in selected industries 
frank strasheim regional chief for federal osha said his staff 
will retain jurisdiction over complaints received before may 1 
federal inspectors will retain responsibility for the safety of 
people who work at federal installations or aboard ships in federal 
waters 
