<TEXT>
george f walker doesnt hesitate to confess his 
amusement and elation at his success in his chosen field of drama 
i just laughed out loud on the subway he said recalling a 
recent ride in his hometown of toronto im a playwright and i 
have children to support 
he laughed again 
the bearded 41yearold walker never has had as successful a 
year as the past one with nothing sacred a staple on the 
repertory theater circuit from los angeles mark taper forum to the 
hartford stage company in connecticut time magazine named it one 
of the 10 best plays of 1988 although it has yet to be performed 
in new york 
the play is his 18th yet walker recalled that when his first 
play was produced it was only the second play he had ever seen 
i was just attracted to the idea that you could fill it up any 
way you want he said to explain his attraction to the theater 
the jovial softspoken walker was in ottawa for the opening of 
nothing sacred in a production very similar to its toronto 
origin at canadas modern national arts center 
walker keeps the 19th century russian setting for his version of 
ivan turgenevs fathers and sons but insists that it now is 
very much a modern canadian work 
he first read the original when he was 17 and said he thinks he 
was in a bit of a trance when he wrote his version 
i never meant it to be an adaptation he said over lunch 
before opening night in ottawa i wrote it in 10 to 11 days 
walker wanted to bill the play as inspired by turgenev but 
then decided that would be hokey 
mostly i thought if i just let it come through me so the 
language would be without being forced for actors living now 
literature was the starting point for nothing sacred just as 
other inspirations have come from something read in the newspaper 
or a conversation with a friend 
im sure if ivan were alive hed be on my side walker said 
about criticism of his adaptation 
much of his earlier work was of a more eccentric tone in line 
with his development in the toronto alternative theater scene of 
the 70s the appeal of the theater he said is its access that 
the multimillion dollar budgets required for movies generally are 
not needed to create plays 
thinking back 12 or 15 years to his early career walker again 
laughed at the contrast to the days when the crowds were smaller 
and the theaters less established 
when youre used to seeing 200 or 300 people come in and then 
you see 800 or 900 he joked where are we going to put them 
all 
walkers toronto agent ralph zimmerman astutely pitched 
nothing sacred last year to american repertory theaters and 
theres been some sniping that the success has as much to do with 
the politics of regional theater as it does with the play 
time reviewing the los angeles production said he 
persuasively makes the debate among student anarchists in 1860s 
russia echo that among marxist collegians of 1960s america 
the new york times gave a decidedly mixed review to the 
production of nothing sacred at hartford stage saying walker 
assumed too much artistic license for a project that could have 
used a bit more reverence 
on the other hand walker believes its time for the dominant 
role of new york reviews to be reevaluated in light of the 
changing theater scene that is less concentrated on broadway 
the playwright also said many canadians gripe about the lack of 
knowledge in the united states about their country but he chalked 
that off to a result of americans selfpreoccupation 
they dont know canada is up here feeling insecure about its 
culture he said they americans are generous come in be 
one of us ive never felt you intruder its kind of positive 
in its own way 
some comment has been made that walker is an example of a 
classic canadian case of gaining legitimacy at home only after 
being discovered in the united states but he believes his steady 
career in toronto was quite established before productions started 
of his plays in us theaters 
i think the message canadians always had was that we didnt 
need to develop our own he said recalling the days when 
canadian theater was dominated by imports from broadway or london 
somewhere along the line you go hey wait i can do that too 
 
and for those canadians who didnt hear about him until 
nothing sacred appeared on times top 10 list walker said 
simply thats ok i read time 
