solving the humanitarian concerns of vietnam 
by law the united states is forbidden to give vietnam any 
financial or material assistance but it does contribute indirectly 
by keeping nongovernment charitable organizations informed of 
vietnams needs and by making it easier for the organizations to 
satisfy complicated regulations in sending goods and people to 
vietnam 
for the families of the missing the vigil is never ending some 
of their children are now older than their fathers were when they 
were lost 
one family rosella and walter fitts have stayed close to their 
home in abington mass near boston for nearly 20 years except to 
attend meetings of the national league of families in washington 
and to speak in new england to keep alive the miapow issue 
we havent been out socially in over 18 years says fitts a 
66yearold bulldozer operator we never go anywhere im afraid 
a phone call will come or a car will come in the driveway with some 
information 
the fittses son richard a special forces green beret 
sergeant has been missing since nov 30 1968 he was only 21 at 
the time married and a father now his only son is 22 older than 
his father was when he was reported missing his wife didnt 
remarry until a year ago 
in march the call the fitts had waited for came military 
officials told mrs fitts that a us excavation team had uncovered 
an undetermined number of human remains at a site in laos where a 
helicopter believed carrying her son and six other military men had 
crashed in november 1968 the remains have been sent to the us 
central identification laboratory 
but marian shelton rosella and walter fitts and others like 
them resist the finality of death 
ive had that feeling right from the beginning that he was 
alive says mrs fitts i just cant get rid of that feeling i 
had a dream of seeing him in a cave alive way back 
fitts says he had hopes his son was alive and suspected he was 
being held in laos by the communist laotian government theyre 
not dashed he says we play the waiting game again 
even if the central identification laboratory confirms the 
remains are those of his son fitts says he would get a second 
independent opinion i would hate to give up and then have him 
walk up the driveway 
fitts clings to the green beret his son sent him for fathers 
day in 1968 shortly before he left for vietnam and to an 
accompanying letter on a piece of yellow lined paper 
when you hold that beret in your hands you hold me 
because we are part of each other please take care if it dad 
treat it like your own son dad because believe it or not 
the beret you hold in front of you is your son 
every morning and every evening the fittses hold the beret in 
their hands 
the minute you pick it up you just feel him that hes right 
there says mrs fitts 
