<TEXT>
 
that could be a typo in the title of the debut album by the 
quasijazz duo of electric guitarist ross traut and bassist steve 
rodby the great yawn would be more like it 
the record is appealing for its sparse texture but once the 
novelty of these simple instrumental arrangements wears off 
theres little to sustain a listeners attention 
the great lawn is most reminiscent of pat metheny traut 
and rodby have both played with him but traut isnt nearly as 
inventive a guitarist he rarely strays far from the melody 
and traut and rodby seem to be waiting for each other to take 
charge as a result the energy level peaks at about a two on a 
10point scale the most animated the duo gets is when rodby 
occasionally slaps his bass 
one wonders how much the label columbia had to do with the 
artists cautious approach to their debut the company hails the 
record as spanning many musical categories jazz new age pop 
rampb and beautiful with traut and rodby trying to please so 
many audiences its a wonder they were able to come up with any 
notes at all 
the great lawn is ok as background music but bring a book 
along 
by steven wine associated press writer 
