the nations economy continued to grown in april 
at a somewhat faster pace than in march but at about the same rate 
as in the first quarter the nations purchasing managers said in a 
report for release today 
the levels of production and new orders both registered 
increases last month after posting declines in the rate of growth 
in march according to the national association of purchasing 
management 
inventory buying did not fuel the pace of the growth as 
inventories declined for the fourth consecutive month said the 
group based in tempe ariz 
new export orders increased at the highest rate since december 
after registering three consecutive months of lower rates of 
growth of the 67 percent of the members who said they export 28 
percent reported better export orders in april up sharply from 22 
percent in both february and march 
the 4 percent who reported lower export orders is down sharply 
from the 9 percent who said so in march 
the economy entered the second quarter on a higher note than 
it ended the first quarter said robert j bretz chairman of the 
industry group 
a surprising increase in new export orders appears to have 
fueled the brisk rebound from marchs sharply lower growth 
nevertheless most other indicators signal a moderate rate of 
growth in the economy in the months ahead he said in a statement 
the groups purchasing managers index climbed to 53 percent in 
april a healthy increase from 504 percent in march this was the 
33rd consecutive month this leading indicator registered over 50 
percent a reading above 50 percent indicates the economy is 
generally expanding below 50 the economy is generally contracting 
bretz said the index averaged 524 percent in the first four 
months of 1989 if that average continues the rest of the year it 
would be consistent with real rate of growth in gross national 
product of about 25 percent he said 
