<TEXT>
the supreme courts decision monday to review 
the partial merger of two detroit newspapers will force 
knightridder inc to determine how much longer it can absorb 
losses from its detroit free press analysts said 
by agreeing to hear arguments on the proposed joint operating 
agreement joa the court set the stage for its first review of 
the 19yearold newspaper preservation act a decision is not 
expected until next year 
the detroit news owned by gannett co inc and the free press 
agreed in 1986 to merge the newspapers production circulation and 
business operations and to split profits and losses equally for 
most of the 100year arrangement 
knightridders president and chief executive officer james k 
battn said the organization would plan over the coming days what 
to do next 
batten said knightridder continues to believe strongly in the 
fairness and justice of our case on behalf of a joa in detroit 
gannett through spokeswoman sheila gibbons said it was 
reviewing the decision and would have no further comment 
both newspapers have been losing money for years and 
knightridder has said it will close the smaller free press unless 
the partial merger goes through 
knightridders decision would be based upon its reading of 
the length of time and the likelihood of this thing 
happening said john s reidy communications industry analyst 
with the new york brokerage house drexel burnham lambert inc 
clearly from their point of view they would like to 
eliminate the cash drain of the free press on the other hand 
if they wait it out then theyll have half interest in a joa 
which will earn considerably more for them than the loss last year 
