<TEXT>
repealing the barriers to interstate banking 
would remove handicaps on the industry in the national and 
international marketplace a member of the federal reserves board 
of governors said monday 
a repeal of such barriers could do much to level the global 
playing field and to restore american banks to prominence around 
the world h robert heller told the bankers association for 
foreign trade at its annual conference 
heller also said repeal of the glasssteagall act which bars 
banks from engaging in securities activities would benefit 
investors and borrowers and give customers better access to the 
securities markets 
he said american banks are retrenching in the world market 
while those in japan and western europe keep enlarging their share 
american banks international lending is down almost 15 percent 
to about 100 billion from its 1983 peak of 121 billion while 
japanese lending has gone from 28 billion to 129 billion german 
and swiss lending has more than doubled and british lending has 
expanded by nearly 50 percent he said 
in addition heller said japanese dominance has extended to the 
us market to no small extent because no bank is permitted to 
have a nationwide presence in the united states 
he said it might be argued more accurately that california and 
new york banks are competing against japanese and german banks 
at yearend 1987 111 japanese banks held over 40 percent of 
the deposits in the 500 largest banks in the world ninety us 
banks were in the top 500 but they accounted for only 11 percent 
of total deposits 
no us bank is among the largest 25 banks in the world and 
japanese banks occupy the top 10 positions he said 
heller said removing the barriers to interstate banking also 
would result in more diversified and safer instutitions a 
highly desirable result in these difficult times 
he said that while the presence of american banks abroad has 
decreased the reverse is true in this country where 259 foreign 
banks operate through subsidiaries branches and agencies with 
combined assets of more than 600 billion about 20 percent of 
total united states banking assets 
he said international banking has increased twice as fast as 
world trade over the past 25 years and four times as fast as world 
gross national product 
he said a new agreement on riskbased capital signed by a dozen 
major industrial nations known as the basle accord should help 
redress inequities among banks incorporated in different nations by 
establishing uniform capital standards for banks that are 
internationally active 
as for the banking and securities issue heller said the fed 
will review the situation within a year with an eye toward 
allowing bank holding companies to engage in underwriting and 
trading equity securities 
the fed recently granted limited securities powers to bank 
holding companies 
he said fulfillment of europes move toward a unified banking 
market and a uniform regulatory environment could mean the 
creation of the largest unified banking market in the world 
however a top european commission official told the group 
separately monday they need not fear a fortress europe or 
reciprocity that would shut them out when the european communitys 
trade barriers fall in 1992 
sir leon brittan vice president of the commission said the 
commissions objective is a liberalized competitive market as open 
as possible to the world 
as long as european community institutions are not discriminated 
against and genuinely have access to american markets bankers in 
this country have nothing to fear he said 
but a west german banking official said the ec should consider 
imposing reciprocity sanctions on japan to put pressure on that 
country to open its banking markets and to liberalize trade much 
as american and british banks have done with some success 
martin kohlhaussen a director of commerzbank in west germany 
said reciprocity is of absolutely no problem to american 
institutions in his country because of good banking relations 
our relations with japan however have not always been of this 
character he said 
kohlhaussen said west germany has used the reciprocity argument 
against japan to press japan for access to its market 
he said that japan often bring up the image of fortress 
europe probably to divert attention from fortress japan 
washington have been assuaged of their fears about a european 
fortress 
but he added that the united states represented a fortress 
where the doors were open but when you came in there were a whole 
lot of compartments a whole lot of rooms that were locked up one 
against the other 
